</FONT><B><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=4><P>Introduction</P>
</B></FONT><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=2>

</B><P>Life is full of theories.   At home and at work, we constantly need to make decisions often relying on our beliefs or theories.   We make theories about the weather, about people, about industrial processes and measurements.   However, making decisions based on unsubstantiated theories is, to say the least, unwise.   Data is collected in order to test a theory.   But how can we use this data to objectively check out a theory?</P>

<P>Our theories will relate to one or more <B>populations</B>.   The data to test our theories will have been collected on <B>samples</B> drawn randomly from the study population(s).  If we were to repeat our data collection, we would obtain a different set of data.</P>

<P>Hypothesis testing offers us an objective method of checking theories or testing one theory against another.</P>

<P>Read the <B>steps of Hypothesis Testing</B> detailed on page 1 of your lecture notes.</P>

<P>We shall consider hypothesis testing in the following situations:</P>

<OL>

<LI>Comparing <B>one sample</B> mean against a ‘standard’ or target value (<FONT FACE="Symbol">&#109;</FONT>
<SUB>0</SUB>).</LI>
<LI>Comparing <B>two independent samples</B> means (assuming equal population variances).</LI>
<LI>Comparing two methods or treatments (<B>paired data</B>).</LI></OL>

<br>
