</FONT><B><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=4><P>Summary</P>
</B></FONT><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=2>
</B>
<P>All the test statistics we have studied take the form:</P>

<B><U><P ALIGN="CENTER">estimate of difference</P>
</U><P ALIGN="CENTER">standard error of difference</P>
</B><P ALIGN="CENTER"></P>
<P>Remember that a standard error is used to mean standard deviation when referring to an estimate.   This distinguishes it from the standard deviation of the sample.   The test statistic is compared to a critical value from the standard normal tables if the standard deviation is known.  The test statistic is compared to a critical value from the t-table if the standard deviation is estimated.   </P>

<P>Page 27 of your lecture notes gives a summary of tests and confidence intervals for one and two samples with the population standard deviation known and unknown.</P>

<P>You may find it helpful to work through the tutorial examples given on pages 28 – 30 of your lecture notes.   Solutions (answers) are given on pages 30-32.</P>

